The people of Macedonia voted in a referendum on Sunday on whether to change its name to the "Republic of North Macedonia", a step that resolves a decades-old dispute with Greece that had blocked its bids for membership in the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which has a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighbourhood in its north represents a possibility of possession of its territory and has vetoed its entry into NATO and the EU.
The two governments reached an agreement in June based on the proposed new name, but nationalist opponents argue that the change weakened the ethnic identity of Macedonia's Slavic majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he would not vote in the referendum and a boycott campaign raised doubts about whether turnout would reach the minimum of 50 per cent required for the referendum to be valid.
The question on the referendum vote reads: 'Are you in favour of NATO and EU membership by accepting the agreement with Greece.'
Those who support the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, argue that it is a reasonable consequence for Macedonia to join bodies such as the EU and NATO, one of the countries that emerged from the collapse of Yugoslavia.
"I have come today to vote for the future of the country, for the young people in Macedonia so that they can live freely under the European Union umbrella because it means a safer life for all of us", said Olivera Georgijevska, 79, in Skopje.
Although not legally binding, enough members of parliament said they would respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
The name change requires a two-thirds majority in parliament.
The state election commission said there were no reports of irregularities as of 1 p.m.
However, turnout was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary election in 2016 when 66% of registered voters cast their ballots.
"I came to vote because of my children, our place is in Europe", said Gjose Tanevski, 62, a voter in the capital, Skopje.
Macedonian PM Zoran Zaev, his wife Zorica and son Dushko voted for the referendum in Macedonia on the change in the country's name giving it the opportunity to join NATO and the European Union in Strumica, Macedonia on 30 September 2018.
Outside the parliament in Skopje, Vladimir Kavardarkov, 54, was throwing a small pole and preparing chairs in front of the tent armed by those who will boycott the referendum.
"We are in favour of NATO and the EU, but we want to enter proudly on our own terms, not by commanding others", Kavadarkov said.
"We are a poor country, but we have our dignity.
If they don't accept us as Macedonia, we can look to others like China and Russia and make us part of the Euro-Asian integration".
Prime Minister Zaev says NATO membership will bring much needed investment to Macedonia, which has an unemployment rate of over 20 per cent.
"I believe that the vast majority will be in favour because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favour of the EU and NATO", Zaev said after voting.
He said that a result in favour of the name change would be "a confirmation of our future".
A poll published on Monday by the Macedonian Institute for Policy Research said that between 30 and 43 percent of voters will take part in the referendum - a figure below the required turnout.
Another survey, conducted by Macedonia's Telma TV, found that 57 percent of respondents were planning to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70 percent said they would vote yes.
For the referendum to be successful, turnout must be 50 per cent and one more vote.
