John Edward: Essential language skills for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools maintain a record of academic excellence, and this was followed in 2018 by another set of excellent exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, the arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, for their chosen career and for their role as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a personalised school curriculum, we are seeing modern languages remain a popular and desirable subject of choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If a man speaks in a language he understands, he understands with his mind.
If you speak in his own language, he understands with his heart".
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely solely on the English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the results of this year's recent examinations, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of students studying foreign languages achieved an A+ grade.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72 per cent of pupils achieved an A+ in Mandarin, while 72 per cent of those studying German, 69 per cent of those studying French and 63 per cent of those studying Spanish also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as vital skills that will undoubtedly be needed by children and young people in the future.
Languages are now, as a subject choice, being kept in the same respect as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and other establishments.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that of the reasons employers gave for posting to fill vacancies, 17 per cent were attributed to lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly imperative in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities and more language-requiring prospects, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career you choose, learning another language will have a real advantage in the future as it has the potential to last you a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries automatically puts a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75 per cent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to maintain a conversation and, at 15 per cent, French is the only language spoken by two-digit percentages.
That is why investing in language learning is now important for today's children.
Knowing more than one language, particularly those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school will learn different languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be of most importance to the UK looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future.
It cannot be denied that at present, in a global business environment, languages remain very important for the future of the country, and this should therefore be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered as "skills of international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
The faut bien le faire. The faut bien is the same as the faut.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
