Harvard students teach a course on getting enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has succeeded in getting all its undergraduate students to sleep more in an effort to combat the growing macho culture of studying all night and staying awake thanks to caffeine.
One academic found that students at the world's top universities often have no idea about the real basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
Finally, a girl came to me and said: "Why are you telling me this now, in my last year?"
