Red Tide update: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The most recent report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decline in Red Tide concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, algal overgrowth conditions in isolated areas are being reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County areas - suggesting decreasing concentrations.
The Red Tide which is an overgrowth of algae extends about 130 miles of coastline from the upper Pinellas to the lower Lee side countries.
Isolated areas can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but at fewer sites related to the past week.
Red Tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations near or off the coast of  Pinellas County were reported in the last week, low to high concentrations off the coast of  Hillsborough County, background for high concentrations in  Manatee County, background for high concentrations near or off the coast of  Sarasota County, background for medium concentrations in  Charlotte County, background for high concentrations near or off the coast of  Lee County, and background for high concentrations in  Collier County.
Respiratory irritation is still reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation was reported in Northwest Florida during the past week.
